The '''Indian Century'''<ref>{{cite book|title=A World Connected|author1=Nayan Chanda|author2=Clyde Prestowitz|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=a_Xhxv5YDjkC&pg=PA19&dq=#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=Yale University Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=American Thought and Culture in the 21st Century|page=10|publisher=Oxford University Press|author1=Martin Halliwell|author2=Catherine Morley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l2k5zrO23aAC&pg=PA10&lpg=PA10&dq=}}</ref> (or '''India's Century'''<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z8Flb0gZ3ZkC&pg=SA35-PA7&dq=%22India%27s+century%22+%22twenty+first%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=w0i7VMiTMsSdNriYgcAB&ved=0CD0Q6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=%22India%20century%22%20%22twenty%20first%22&f=false|title=Political Science for Civil Services Main Examination|first=N.|last=D. Arora|pages=35–7|publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill Education}}</ref>) is the possibility that the 21st century will be dominated by [[India]], similarly to how the 20th century is often called the [[American Century]],<ref name="UNI">[http://news.oneindia.in/2007/12/01/21st-century-is-going-to-be-indian-century-alagappan-1196517764.html "21st century is going to be Indian century: Alagappan."] December 1, 2007. OneIndia News/(UNI).</ref> and the 19th century as [[Pax Britannica]] (British Peace).<ref name=Halliwell>{{cite book|last=Halliwell|first=Martin|title=American Thought and Culture in the 21st Century|year=2008|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-0748626021|pages=9–10|author2=Catherine Morley}}</ref> The phrase is used particularly in the assertion<ref name="India US Russia World Economy">{{cite web|title=India will overtake the US to become the world's second biggest economy by 2050, with Russia becoming Europe's most powerful financial nation, economists predict |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-4199660/India-overtake-world-s-second-largest-economy.html|work=[[Daily Mail]], UK|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> that the [[economy of India]] could overtake<ref name="India US Russia World Economy"/><ref name="Economic Order International">{{cite web|title=The West and the Rest in the International Economic Order|url=http://oecdobserver.org/news/archivestory.php/aid/884/The_West_and_the_Rest_in_the_International_Economic_Order.html|work=[[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]]|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref><ref name="2050 Word Economy">{{cite news|title=China, India to Overtake U.S. Economy by 2050|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2017-02-07/china-india-to-overtake-us-economy-by-2050|publisher=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref> the [[economy of the United States]] and [[economy of China]] as the [[List of countries by GDP (nominal)|largest national economy in the world]],<ref name="Hindu">{{cite news|title=Of Oxford, economics, empire, and freedom|newspaper=The Hindu|url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/07/10/stories/2005071002301000.htm|location=Chennai|date=2 October 2005|accessdate=2010-12-06}}</ref> a position [[Economic history of India|it held]]<ref name="British India">{{cite book | title = An Era of Darkness: The British Empire in India| publisher=Aleph Book Company| isbn =978-9383064656 }}</ref> from 1 to 1500 A.D. and in 1700 A.D.<ref>http://glavkonstruktor.ru/upload/img/ADFQtcg.png</ref><ref>Data Source: Tables of Prof. Angus Maddison (2010). The per capita GDP over various years and population data can be downloaded in a spreadsheet from [http://www.ggdc.net/maddison/oriindex.htm here].</ref>
India has created [[North–South Transport Corridor]] as an alternative to [[One Belt, One Road]] policy initiative of China (PRC),<ref name="India TIR">{{cite web|title=India ratifies TIR Convention to access transnational multi-modal connectivity|url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/dqvNmMJGbqQAC8pYZPAYdI/India-ratifies-TIR-Convention-to-access-transnational-multi.html|work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="India Silk Road">{{cite web|title=Watch Out, China: India Is Building A 'New Silk Road' Of Its Own|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/wadeshepard/2017/06/28/watch-out-china-india-is-building-a-new-silk-road-of-its-own/#515c8a5a90ec|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="India OBOR Counter">{{cite web|title=PM Modi in Russia: How fastracking North-South corridor will help India counter Chinese OBOR|url=http://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/pm-modi-in-russia-how-fastracking-north-south-corridor-will-help-india-counter-chinese-obor/696639/|work=[[The Financial Express (India)]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> to link in with Iran, Russia, the Caucasus, and Central Asia. In 2017, India and [[Japan]]<ref name="India Japan AAGC">{{cite web|title=India And Japan Join Forces To Counter China And Build Their Own New Silk Road|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/wadeshepard/2017/07/31/india-and-japan-join-forces-to-counter-china-and-build-their-own-new-silk-road/#2fb1ae0b4982|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref><ref name="India Japan AAGC2">{{cite web|title=Ignoring OBOR, India and Japan forge ahead with joint connectivity project|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/ignoring-obor-india-and-japan-forge-ahead-with-joint-connectivity-project/articleshow/59830218.cms|work=[[The Economic Times]]|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> joined together to form [[Asia-Africa Growth Corridor]], to better integrate the economies of South, Southeast, and East Asia with Oceania and Africa.<ref name="India Japan AAGC"/><ref name="India Japan AAGC2"/>
According to the report named "Indian Century: Defining India's Place in a Rapidly Changing Global Economy" by [[IBM]] Institute for Business Value, India is predicted to be among the world’s highest-growth nations over the coming years.<ref name="IBM India Century">{{cite web|title=Indian Century - Defining India’s place in a rapidly changing global economy|url=http://public.dhe.ibm.com/common/ssi/ecm/gb/en/gbe03681usen/GBE03681USEN.PDF|work=[[IBM]]|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref><ref name="IBM 21">{{cite web|title=India to be world's highest growth nation in 21st century: IBM study|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/economy-policy/india-to-be-world-s-highest-growth-nation-in-21st-century-ibm-study-115121000918_1.html|work=[[Business Standard]]|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref><ref name="IBM">{{cite web|title=21st century is India's century: IBM chief Virginia Rometty|url=http://www.moneycontrol.com/news/economy/21st-century-is-indias-century-ibm-chief-virginia-rometty_1963021.html|work=[[Moneycontrol.com]]|accessdate=11 February 2016}}</ref>
==Factors== One of the key factors includes its populous democracy.<ref>[http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/Business/India-s-decade-could-pave-way-for-an-Indian-century/Article1-492147.aspx "‘India’s decade could pave way for an Indian century’."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508030100/http://www.hindustantimes.com/News-Feed/Business/India-s-decade-could-pave-way-for-an-Indian-century/Article1-492147.aspx |date=2013-05-08 }} ''Hindustan Times.''</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.omantribune.com/index.php?page=news&id=61484&heading=India|title=Next century will be India's, says WSJ - Oman Tribune|work=omantribune|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150119002835/http://www.omantribune.com/index.php?page=news&id=61484&heading=India|archivedate=2015-01-19|df=}}</ref> As per [[United Nations]] report, India will overtake China to become the world's most populous nation by 2022.<ref name="India WP">{{cite web|title=India 'to overtake China's population by 2022' - UN|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-33720723|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="WP UN">{{cite web|title=World Population Prospects 2017 - UN|url=https://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/|work=[[United Nations]]|accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref>
Economists and Researchers at [[Harvard University]] have projected India’s 7% projected annual growth rate through 2024 would continue to put it ahead of China, making India the fastest growing economy in the world.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Growth Projections Predict the Rise of India, East Africa and Fall of Oil Economies|url=http://www.hks.harvard.edu/news-events/news/articles/new-growth-projections|accessdate=12 April 2016|date=7 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=India Will Be Fastest-Growing Economy for Coming Decade, Harvard Researchers Predict|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2016/01/01/india-will-be-fastest-growing-economy-for-coming-decade-harvard-researchers-predict/|accessdate=12 April 2016|date=1 January 2016}}</ref> In 2017, Center for International Development at Harvard University, published a research study,<ref name="2025 Projections Harvard"/> projecting that India has emerged<ref name="2025 Projections Harvard"/> as the economic pole of global growth by surpassing China and is expected to maintain its lead over the coming decade.<ref name="2025 Projections Harvard">{{cite web|title=New 2025 Global Growth Projections Predict China’s Further Slowdown and the Continued Rise of India|url=http://atlas.cid.harvard.edu/rankings/growth-predictions/|work=[[Harvard University]]|accessdate=10 July 2017}}</ref>
India is generally considered an emerging power due to its large and stable population, and its rapidly growing economic and military sectors.<ref>{{cite news|title=Real India: A Historian's Cautions on "The Indian Century" (AUDIO)|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/christopher-lydon/real-india-a-historians-c_b_673262.html|first=Christopher|last=Lydon|work=Huffington Post|date=6 August 2010}}</ref>
